description: Inhibition of recombinant human CYP3A4 expressed in baculosomes using BOMR as substrate preincubated for 10 mins followed by substrate/NADP+ addition measured for 1 hr
text_summary: The experimental conditions of the assay for the CYP3A4 IC50 measurement were: - Human recombinant CYP3A4 enzymes were expressed in microsomes of insect cells at a concentration of 1000 pg/ml. - The test compounds were dissolved in acetonitrile 100% v/v (10 mM) and prepared as titrations in reaction buffer (potassium phosphate, 200 mM). - Total CYP3A4 activity was quantified in the presence of test compounds as determined by the manufacture (Vivid CYP3A4 RED Screening Kit, Thermo Fisher Scientific).  The method used to determine the IC50 value is: - The percent inhibition due to the presence of each compound was obtained as the ratio between the rate observed in the presence of test compounds and the rate observed in the presence of the positive inhibition control (Ketoconazole). - The CYP3A4 activity was monitored for 1 hour using a Synergy H4 Hybrid multi-Mode Biotek microplate reader (Excitation: 535/Emission 590, bandwidth 20 with 1 min interval between readings).  The IC50 value for compound 4 was 155.7 ± 63.4 μM.

text_summary: Here is the condensed statement:  The IC50 value of 96.9 uM was determined using the Vivid CYP450 assay principle, which is based on the conversion of a substrate to a highly fluorescent chromophore by human CYP450 enzyme, measured as relative fluorescence units (RFUs). The assay was performed with substrate concentrations of 0.01, 0.1, 1, 10, and 20 µM, using microsomes prepared from insect cells expressing recombinant human CYP450 enzyme, human CYP450 reductase, and a glucose-6-phosphate/glucose-6-phosphate dehydrogenase system in 100 mM potassium phosphate buffer (pH 8.0), and incubated for 10 min at room temperature. The IC50 value was calculated as half maximal inhibitory concentrations, and the results were reported as the average IC50 ± standard deviation (SD) of two independent experiments (n = 3).
